	<item>
		<title>Stacks project website slow</title>
		<link>https://www.math.columbia.edu/~dejong/wordpress/?p=5022</link>
					<comments>https://www.math.columbia.edu/~dejong/wordpress/?p=5022#respond</comments>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Johan]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Fri, 22 May 2026 15:57:16 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://www.math.columbia.edu/~dejong/wordpress/?p=5022</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[We&#8217;re having problems with bots hammering the site. For example since this morning we&#8217;ve got 65 thousand requests for bibliography items (and it isn&#8217;t noon yet). As we have only 700 bibliography entries, this means there are more than 90 &#8230; <a href="https://www.math.columbia.edu/~dejong/wordpress/?p=5022">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&#8594;</span></a>]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>We&#8217;re having problems with bots hammering the site. For example since this morning we&#8217;ve got 65 thousand requests for bibliography items (and it isn&#8217;t noon yet). As we have only 700 bibliography entries, this means there are more than 90 bots each requesting the entire bibliography &#8212; some kind of botnet that&#8217;s going wild.</p>
<p>While these idiotic bibliography requests are a new problem, heavy traffic due to bots is not a new problem. It&#8217;s frustrating as any smart web-crawler would understand that all the information could be obtained by downloading the entire stacks project from github in one fell swoop. An example is 36K requests from openai/bot just today; more than 10% of our traffic (although these weren&#8217;t causing the problem we had).</p>
<p>Meanwhile I apologize to any humans still reading the Stacks Project!</p>
<p>PS: We had to temporarily block access to the bibliography pages.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
					<wfw:commentRss>https://www.math.columbia.edu/~dejong/wordpress/?feed=rss2&#038;p=5022</wfw:commentRss>
			<slash:comments>0</slash:comments>
		
		
			</item>
